As already suggested, there are built-in ways to do this.  But your method is rather confusing and has a lot of unnecessary code. But here are some suggestions.

**Your `j_delete_char` method has problems.**

The idea is simple.
- create a new array one less that the original, since you will be deleting one character.
- then copy characters except the one at `index` to the new array.
```
public static String j_delete_char(String s, int index) {
    if (index &gt;= s.length()) {
        return s;
    }
```
first, copy all the chars from 0 to index-1
```
   for (int i = 0; i &lt; index; i++) {  
      ret_s_array[i] = s_array[i];
   }
```
then copy all the characters from the index to destination, starting with the first character beyond the index.
```
   for (int i = index; i &lt; ret_s_array.length; i++) {
      ret_s_array[i] = s_array[i+1];
   }

   return Arrays.toString(ret_s_array);
}

```
**Problems with the `j_delete_all_chars` method**

Your first part of the `j_delete_all_chars` finds out many to be deleted.  This can be used to create a proper length `result array` of characters. This is fine.  But your second loop is incorrect.  And you are creating an array of Strings based on the delete count which doesn&#39;t make sense.
```
char[] s_array = s.toCharArray();
int to_del_cnt = 0;
for (int i = 0; i &lt; s.length(); i++) {
    if (s_array[i] == to_del) {
        to_del_cnt += 1; // in java you can also do `to_del_cnt++`
    }
}
```
So now create the result array.  Original length minus the number to be deleted.
```
char [] result = new char[s.length() - to_del_cnt];
```
Now just iterate over the existing string of characters and if the `currentChar` does **not** equal the one to be deleted, add it to the `result array` and `increment the index`.
```
int index = 0;
for (int i = 0; i &lt; s.length(); i++) {
    char currentChar = s.charAt(i);
    if (currentChar != to_del) 
        result[index++] = currentChar;
    }
}
return Arrays.toString(result);
```
You could also just do the following which converts the `to_del` character to a string and replaces all occurrences with an empty string.  
```
s = s.replace(to_del+&quot;&quot;, &quot;&quot;);             // returns a string
return Arrays.toString(s.toCharArray());  // returns the array as a string
```

The problem is that `Arrays.toString(char[])` is not the reverse of `String.toCharArray()`.

The `j_delete_char()` does not return a string with the character at the index deleted, it returns a string represention of the character array:

`j_delete_char(&quot;abcdef&quot;, 3)` returns `&quot;[a, b, c, e, f]&quot;` when it should probably return `&quot;abcef&quot;`.

Because of this the `j_delete_all_chars(&quot;abcdef22abcd&quot;, &#39;2&#39;)` produces these intermediate results:

- Input String: `&quot;abcdef22abcd&quot;`
- First &#39;2&#39; replaced: `&quot;[a, b, c, d, e, f, 2, a, b, c, d]&quot;`
- Second &#39;2&#39; replaced: `&quot;[[, a, ,,  , b, ,,  , c, ,,  , d, ,,  , e, ,,  , f, ,,  , ,,  , a, ,,  , b, ,,  , c, ,,  , d, ]]&quot;`
- Creating the result string: `[[, [, ,,  , a, ,,  , ,, ,,  ,  , ,,  , b, ,,  , ,, ,,  ,  , ,,  , c, ,,  , ,, ,,  ,  , ,,  , d, ,,  , ,, ,,  ,  , ,,  , e, ,,  , ,, ,,  ,  , ,,  , f, ,,  , ,, ,,  ,  , ,,  , ,, ,,  ,  , ,,  , a, ,,  , ,, ,,  ,  , ,,  , b, ,,  , ,, ,,  ,  , ,,  , c, ,,  , ,, ,,  ,  , ,,  , d, ,,  , ], ]]`


What you probably wanted in your `j_delete_char()` method is to create a new String from the `char[]` using `new String(char[])`:

    public static String j_delete_char(String s, int index) {
        if (index &gt;= s.length()) {
            return s;
        }

        char[] s_array = s.toCharArray();
        char[] ret_s_array = new char[s.length() - 1];

        for (int i = index; i &lt; s.length() - 1; i++) {
            s_array[i] = s_array[i + 1];
        }

        for (int i = 0; i &lt; s.length() - 1; i++) {
            ret_s_array[i] = s_array[i];
        }

        return new String(ret_s_array);
    }

And also the last line of `j_delete_all_chars()` is nonsense. `ds[to_del_cnt]` already contains a reference to the string with the characters replaced and therefore you should just return it:

    public static String j_delete_all_chars(String s, char to_del) {
        // ... code as before except the last line
        return ds[to_del_cnt];
    }

Here is a re-factor.

```java
String j_delete_char(String s, int index) {
    if (index &gt;= s.length()) return s;
    return s.substring(0, index) + s.substring(index + 1);
}

String j_delete_all_chars(String s, char to_del) {
    for (int i = 0; i &lt; s.length(); i++)
        if (s.charAt(i) == to_del) s = j_delete_char(s, i--);
    return s;
}
```

If you wanted to keep the _array_ in _j_delete_char_, for practice; here is an example.

```java
String j_delete_char(String s, int index) {
    if (index &gt;= s.length()) return s;
    char[] a = new char[s.length() - 1];
    int i, n;
    for (i = 0, n = index; i &lt; n; i++) a[i] = s.charAt(i);
    for (i = index + 1, n = s.length(); i &lt; n; i++)
        a[i - 1] = s.charAt(i);
    return new String(a);
}
```

Or, utilize the _[Arrays#copyOfRange](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/21/docs/api/java.base/java/util/Arrays.html#copyOfRange(char[],int,int))_, and _[System#arraycopy](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/21/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/System.html#arraycopy(java.lang.Object,int,java.lang.Object,int,int))_, methods.

```java
String j_delete_char(String s, int index) {
    if (index &gt;= s.length()) return s;
    char[] a = s.toCharArray(), x, y;
    x = Arrays.copyOfRange(a, 0, index);
    y = Arrays.copyOfRange(a, index + 1, a.length);
    a = new char[s.length() - 1];
    System.arraycopy(x, 0, a, 0, x.length);
    System.arraycopy(y, 0, a, x.length, y.length);
    return new String(a);
}
```

Alternately, use the _[StringBuilder](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/21/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/StringBuilder.html)_ class.

```java
String j_delete_all_chars(String s, char to_del) {
    StringBuilder b = new StringBuilder(s);
    String t = String.valueOf(to_del);
    while (b.toString().contains(t)) b.deleteCharAt(b.indexOf(t));
    return b.toString();
}
```

Or, the _[String#replace](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/21/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/String.html#replace(java.lang.CharSequence,java.lang.CharSequence))_ method.

```java
&quot;abcdef222abcd&quot;.replace(&quot;2&quot;, &quot;&quot;)
```

You might take this kind of approach to deal with the issues dealt with in my comments above:
```
    public static String deleteCharacter(String s, int codepoint) {
        return s.codePoints().
            filter(c -&gt;c != codepoint).
            collect(StringBuilder::new, StringBuilder::appendCodePoint, StringBuilder::append).toString();
    }
```
To get the codepoint in question, you might do something like `int codepoint = &quot;&#129322;&quot;.codePointAt(0);`

Be simple!
```java
public static String j_delete_all_chars(String str, char ch) {
    StringBuilder buf = new StringBuilder();

    for (int i = 0; i &lt; str.length(); i++)
        if (str.charAt(i) != ch)
            buf.append(str.charAt(i));

    return Arrays.toString(buf.toString().toCharArray());
}
```

